Assignment 1: Compression of a YCbCr colored image¶

Introduction¶

The following notebook collects my solution to compress a custom colored image. In particular I provided to blurr the various YCbCr channels following the assignment instructions.

For the implementation of the exercise I used theese libraries and packages.

Transformation with Gaussian Filter¶

Filter on Y channel (Luma)¶

In [ ]:
im_filtered = im_ycbcr.copy()

As first transformation I applied a Gaussian filter on the Luma channel Y of the image im_ycbcr.

To verify the behaviour of different standard deviations of the filter's kernel, I tested 3 $σ$ as follows:

  • sigma1 = (5,5)
  • sigma2 = (50,50)
  • sigma1 = (5,50)
In [ ]:
sigma1 = (5,5)

# Gaussian Filter with sd = 5 for both axes
im_filtered[:,:,0] = filters.gaussian(im_ycbcr[:,:,0], sigma1, truncate=3.5,
                                      multichannel=True)

# Subplots comparing original and blurred image
plt.subplot(1,2,1); plt.imshow(im_ycbcr[:,:,0], cmap='gray')
plt.title('Luma Y')
plt.subplot(1,2,2); plt.imshow(im_filtered[:,:,0], cmap='gray')
plt.title('Blurred Luma Y')
Out[ ]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Blurred Luma Y')

Because $σ_1$ is not a value too high, the effect deriving from the transformation it's an image very close to the original one. So I decided to set a standard deviation much higher.

In [ ]:
im_filtered_y = im_ycbcr.copy()
sigma2 = (50,50)

# Gaussian Filter with sd = 50 for both axes
im_filtered_y[:,:,0] = filters.gaussian(im_ycbcr[:,:,0], sigma2, truncate=3.5,
                                      multichannel=True)

# Subplots comparing original and blurred image
plt.subplot(1,2,1); plt.imshow(im_ycbcr[:,:,0], cmap='gray')
plt.title('Luma Y')
plt.subplot(1,2,2); plt.imshow(im_filtered_y[:,:,0], cmap='gray')
plt.title('Blurred Luma Y')
Out[ ]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Blurred Luma Y')

With a $\sigma_2=50$ for both the axes, the obtained image with the Gaussian filter is a very blurred image in which it is not possible to distinguish any original detail.

Lastly I tried to assign some different values of $\sigma$ for each axis.

In [ ]:
sigma3 = (5,50)

# Gaussian Filter with sd_x = 5 and sd_y = 50
im_filtered[:,:,0] = filters.gaussian(im_ycbcr[:,:,0], sigma3, truncate=3.5,
                                      multichannel=True)

# Subplots comparing original and blurred image
plt.subplot(1,2,1); plt.imshow(im_ycbcr[:,:,0], cmap='gray')
plt.title('Luma Y')

The output image is less blurred than the previous one but it present a "rough" effect due to the differences in $\sigma$.

Image Convertion from RGB to YCbCr¶

In the last phase of the assignment I proceeded to reconvert the images processed in the previous paragraphs in the RGB color space.

In particular I have selected only the images with $\sigma = 50$ for each paragraph, as the changes applied by the filter are more likely to be observed.

First of all I defined a colorization(im) function which, taken as input the modified image and in RGB space, returns an image whose values have been normalized in the $[0,1]$ range and scaled to $255$. Furthermore, the values of the image have been converted from float64 to uint8.

In [ ]:
def colorization(im):

  # Data normalization in 0 - 1 and
  # data scaled to 255 with casting to uint8

  im[im > 1.] = 1
  im[im < 0.] = 0
  im = (im * 255).astype(np.uint8)

  return im
In [ ]:
# Conversion from YCbCr to RGB
im1_rgb = color.ycbcr2rgb(im_filtered_y)

# Function application to normalize data
im1_rgb = colorization(im1_rgb)

# Subplots comparing original and new image in RGB
plt.subplot(1,2,1); plt.imshow(im); plt.title('Original Image')
plt.subplot(1,2,2); plt.imshow(im1_rgb); plt.title('Blurred Luma Image')
Out[ ]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Blurred Luma Image')

The image filtered on channel Y, as seen previously in grayscale, appears to have undergone the greatest and sharpest distortions compared to its sharpness. Subsequent images, with the filter applied to the chroma channels, appear to have been less distorted.

However, the modified image on both channels at the same time is slightly more distorted and blurry than the other two.
